\begin_layout Abstract
In this project we try to deblur images where the blur is spatially variant
 - that is, depending on the position of the image - and do so in a computationa
lly effective way.
 In the lecture, image deblurring was formulated as a convex optimization
 problem, and discretized with the 
\emph on
discrete convolution
\emph default
, a linear operator 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 If the blur is spatially 
\emph on
invariant
\emph default
, the discrete convolution 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is represented by a Toeplitz or block circulant matrix, and we can use
 the Discrete Fourier Transform (DFT) for efficient matrix operations.
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(n\log n)$
\end_inset

 ?
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If the blur is spatially 
\emph on
variant
\emph default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is non-Toeplitz in general.
\end_layout

