\begin_layout Standard
In image deblurring, we seek to recover the original, sharp image by using
 a mathematical model of the blurring process.
 This process is assumed to be 
\emph on
linear
\emph default
: if 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 are the blurred versions of the exact images 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\alpha f_{1}+\beta f_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the blurred image of 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\alpha u_{1}+\beta u_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Linear models can describe several physical mechanisms such as relative
 motion between the camera and subject (motion blur), bad focusing (defocusing
 blur), or a number of other mechanisms 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Afonso-2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In other cases, knowledge of the physical process that causes the blur provides
 an explicit formulation of the PSF.
 When this is the case, the elements of the PSF array are given by a precise
 mathematical expression
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The continous image acquisition model is, in particular, given by the integral:
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Nagy-1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(s)=\int_{\mathbb{R}^{2}}p(s,t)u(t)\,\text{d}t,\quad s\in Q\label{eq:continuous-model-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 describes the PSF (
\emph on
point-spread function
\emph default
), 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 the exact image, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 the observed (blurred) image, and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\subset\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 the 
\emph on
field of view
\emph default
.
 In the usual applications in astronomy, microscopy and photographic imaging,
 the PSF has finite width 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Calvetti-2005"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(s,t)\approx0\quad\text{for}\quad\|s-t\|>\delta,\ \delta>0.
\]

\end_inset

Thus, we can restrict the integral to the 
\emph on
extended field of view
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $B=Q+D_{\delta}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\delta}$
\end_inset

 denotes a disc of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 centered at the origin.
 (Compare Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:The-PSF-spills"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The observed image 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 contains no information of the true scenery outside of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We now divide 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{B}$
\end_inset

 identical pixels of area 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 (assumed 
\begin_inset Formula $\equiv1$
\end_inset

), with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 pixels inside the field of view:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(s_{l})=\sum_{k=1}^{n_{B}}p(s_{l},t_{k})u(t_{k}),\qquad1\leq l\leq n\label{eq:discrete-model-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We limit ourselves to estimating the image 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 from the data within the field of view 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 The observed image contains no information of the true scenery outside
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 We thus use one of the following (artificial) boundary conditions: 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "4.1 Basic Structures"
key "Hansen-2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
which specify our assumptions on the scene just outside our image
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\series bold
zero boundary condition
\series default
 is a good choice when the exact image is mostly zero outside the boundaryâ€”as
 is the case for many astronomical images with a black background.
 Unfortunately, the zero boundary condition has a bad effect on reconstructions
 of images that are nonzero outside the border.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\series bold
periodic boundary condition
\series default
 is frequently used in image processing.
 This implies that the image repeats itself (endlessly) in all directions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In some applications it is reasonable to use a 
\series bold
reflexive boundary condition
\series default
, which implies that the scene outside the image boundaries is a mirror
 image of the scene inside the image boundaries.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
When the blur introduced by the image acquisition process is 
\emph on
spatially invariant
\emph default
, the PSF 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 does not depend on the spatial location 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, and can be specified by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(s,t)=p(s-t)\label{eq:psf-invariant}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the sum becomes the two-dimensional convolution operation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "4.1"
key "Yun-2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
In this project we assume the point-spread function is a 
\emph on
known 
\emph default
quantity, for example by deriving experimentally from point sources (such
 as fluorescent beads in microscopy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Stuurman-2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 If the blurring model is not known, or not with sufficient accuracy, we
 speak of 
\emph on
blind deblurring
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Almeida-2010"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Matrix formulation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Matrix-formulation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can arrange the elements of the images 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 into column vectors
\emph on
 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{vec}(f)$
\end_inset


\emph default
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{vec}(u)$
\end_inset

, by stacking an 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times N$
\end_inset

 image into an 
\begin_inset Formula $n=MN$
\end_inset

 vector.
 The equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:discrete-model-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) can then be written as a linear system:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{vec}(f)=A\,\text{vec}(u).\label{eq:discrete-model-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For images of sizes 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times N$
\end_inset

, the sizes of vectors are 
\begin_inset Formula $MN\times1$
\end_inset

, and the size of the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $MN\times MN$
\end_inset

.
 The construction of this matrix is described in detail in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "4. Structured Matrix Computations"
key "Hansen-2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
When denoting images 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, we assume them to be in column vector format from now on.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 describes spatially invariant blur, the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has a specific structure depending on the boundary conditions described
 above.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
BCCB
\emph default
 (block circulant with circulant blocks) for periodic boundary conditions,
 and 
\emph on
Toeplitz-plus-Hankel
\emph default
 for reflexive boundary conditions.
 Matrix computations can then be implemented efficiently with the Discrete
 Fourier transform (DFT) and Discrete Cosine Transform (DCT), respectively
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "4.2.2, 4.3"
key "Hansen-2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With 
\emph on
spatially variant
\emph default
 blur, this is no longer the case.
 In this case, there is not a single PSF that can be used to represent the
 blurring operation; point sources in different locations of the image may
 result in different PSFs.
 In the most general case, there is a different PSF for each pixel in the
 image.
 Here we consider situations where there is a continuous and smooth variation
 in the PSF with respect to the position of the point source.
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It is not computationally feasible to construct all of these PSFs, so other
 approaches to representing K need to be considered.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
When spatial invariance is a poor approximation of the actual blur, or when
 periodic boundary conditions are poor approximations to the extended true
 image scene, the quality of reconstructions will be limited.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

