\begin_layout Standard
In this project, 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
second issue is out of scope (Bayesian approach)
\end_layout

\end_inset

we approach the first issue by adding 
\emph on
regularizers
\emph default
, in a constrained optimization problem of the form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\min_{u\in\mathbb{R}^{n}}\phi(u)\quad\text{subject to}\quad\|Au-f\|_{2}\leq\varepsilon\label{eq:constrained-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\mathbb{R}^{n}\rightarrow\overline{\mathbb{R}}=\mathbb{R}\cup\{-\infty,+\infty\}$
\end_inset

 is a regularization function, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\geq0$
\end_inset

 a parameter which depends upon the noise variance.
 This can be written as the unconstrained problem:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\min_{u\in\mathbb{R}^{n}}\phi(u)+\delta_{B(\varepsilon,f)}(Au)\label{eq:unconstrained-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is the indicator function on the closed ball 
\begin_inset Formula $B(\varepsilon,y)$
\end_inset

 of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

, centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 To limit the dynamic range of the solution, we add the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq x_{i}\leq1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in[n]$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "4.2"
key "Yun-2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This results in the unconstrained problem: 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We also mention that when the majority of the elements in the image f are
 zero or near zero, as may be the case for astronomical or medical images,
 it may be wise to enforce nonnegativity constraints on the solution [4,
 6, 102].
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\min_{u\in\mathbb{R}^{n}}J(u) & :=\min_{u\in\mathbb{R}^{n}}\phi(u)+\delta_{B(\varepsilon,f)}(Au)+\delta_{[0,1]^{n}}(u)\label{eq:unconstrained-2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Popular choices for the regularizer are 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(u)=\|u\|_{1}$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{1}$
\end_inset

 norm, and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi(u)=TV(u)=\sum_{i=1}^{n}|u_{i}-u_{i-1}|,
\]

\end_inset

the 1-dimensional discrete total variation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Existence of solution
\end_layout

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is proper, convex and lower semi-continuous (such as TV), then the functional
 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 is proper, convex and lower semi-continuous (note that 
\begin_inset Formula $B(\epsilon,f)$
\end_inset

 is non-empty).
 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 is also coercive, because 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{[0,1]^{n}}$
\end_inset

 is coercive by boundedness of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that problem (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:unconstrained-2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) has a solution.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
1-d TV is strictly convex, indicators?
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

