\begin_layout Subsection
Algorithms
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Algorithms"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the regularizer is convex, problem (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:constrained-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is convex, but the very high dimensions (often 
\begin_inset Formula $\gg10^{6})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, and possibly 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

, preclude direct application of off-the-shelf optimization algorithms.
 Efficient restoration algorithms, such as those described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Afonso-2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, make assumptions on the structure of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Specifically, spatially invariant blur with a periodic boundary condition
 results in a block circulant matrix.
 This matrix has a spectral decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula $A=F^{\ast}\Lambda F$
\end_inset

 given by the DFT matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 (which, assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2^{k}$
\end_inset

, can be computed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(n\log_{2}n)$
\end_inset

 time, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "4.2.1"
key "Hansen-2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.) This in turn allows many matrix computions to be performed efficiently.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Fortunately the matrix K can usually be represented by a compact data structure,
 such as when the blur is spatially invariant.
 (mention sparsity patterns)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case of spatially variant blur (that is, the PSF changes depending
 on the location of pixels in an observed image), the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is no longer block-circulant, Toeplitz, or even symmetric.
 We may instead attempt to find an approximate solution in a 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

-dimensional subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $m\ll n$
\end_inset

.
