\begin_layout Standard
The problem (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:unconstrained-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) can be seen as an unconstrained optimization problem of the form 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
notation: 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 used priorly for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

real image
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\min_{u\in\mathbb{R}^{n}}f_{1}(u)+f_{2}(Gu)\label{eq:split-problem-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $G\in\mathbb{R}^{d\times n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}:\mathbb{R}^{n}\rightarrow\overline{\mathbb{R}}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}:\mathbb{R}^{d}\rightarrow\overline{\mathbb{R}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Variable splitting
\emph default
 is a simple procedure that consists in creating a new variable, say 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

, to serve as the argument of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

, under the constraints that 
\begin_inset Formula $v=Gu$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "II.A"
key "Afonso-2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\min_{u\in\mathbb{R}^{n},\,v\in\mathbb{R}^{d}}f_{1}(u)+f_{2}(v)\quad\text{subject to}\quad Gu-v=0.\label{eq:split-problem-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The rationale behind variable splitting is that it may be easier to solve
 the constrained problem (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:split-problem-2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) than to solve its equivalent unconstrained counterpart (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:split-problem-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) We now form the 
\emph on
augmented Lagrangian
\emph default
 for this problem:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{\mu}(u,v,\lambda)=f_{1}(u)+f_{2}(v)+\lambda^{T}(Au-v)+\frac{\mu}{2}\|Gu-v\|_{2}^{2}
\]

\end_inset

Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $(u,v)$
\end_inset

 is a feasible solution, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{\mu}(u,v,\lambda)=f_{1}(u)+f_{2}(v).
\]

\end_inset

ADMM minimizes 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 through the iterations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "3.1"
key "Boyd-2010"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
u_{k+1} & \in\argmin_{u}L_{\mu}(u,v_{k},\lambda_{k}),\nonumber \\
v_{k+1} & \in\argmin_{v}L_{\mu}(u_{k+1},v,\lambda_{k}),\label{eq:admm-iteration}\\
\lambda_{k+1} & \in\lambda^{k}+\mu(Au_{k+1}-v_{k+1}).\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

By setting the residual 
\begin_inset Formula $r:=Gu-v$
\end_inset

 and the 
\emph on
scaled dual variable 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $d:=-\frac{1}{\mu}\lambda$
\end_inset

, we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lambda^{T}r+\frac{\mu}{2}\|r\|_{2}^{2} & =(\mu/2)\|r+(\mu/2)\lambda\|_{2}^{2}-(1/2\mu)\|\lambda\|_{2}^{2}\\
 & =(\mu/2)\|r-d\|_{2}^{2}-(\mu/2)\|d\|_{2}^{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The removal of constant factors then results in the 
\emph on
scaled formulation
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
u_{k+1}\in & \argmin_{u}f_{1}(u)+\frac{\mu}{2}\|Gu-v_{k}-d_{k}\|_{2}^{2},\nonumber \\
v_{k+1}\in & \argmin_{v}f_{2}(v)+\frac{\mu}{2}\|Gu_{k+1}-v-d_{k}\|_{2}^{2},\label{eq:admm-scaled}\\
d_{k+1}= & d_{k}-(Gu_{k+1}-v_{k+1}).\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 is proper, convex and lsc, then the 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{k}$
\end_inset

 update uniquely exists, and can be written using the 
\emph on
proximal operator
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{k+1}=\prox_{f_{2}/\mu}(Gu_{k+1}-d_{k}).
\]

\end_inset

For problem (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:unconstrained-2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), we describe the proximal operators in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Proximal-operators"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Because it contains more than 2 summands, we generalize ADMM in Section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Generalized-ADMM"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to handle 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 summands.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Convergence
\end_layout

\end_inset

Under the assumptions that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 are both closed, proper and convex, that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has full column rank, and that both subproblems are solved exactly, then
 ADMM is shown to converge.
 As long as the sequence of errors is absolutely summable, convergence is
 not compromised 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Theorem 1"
key "Afonso-2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The convergence rate is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(1/k)$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{\mu}(u^{k})-L_{\mu}(u^{\ast})=\mathcal{O}(1/k)
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 the iteration number 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "He-2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We do not know of a convergence result for ADMM in 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

-dimensional (Krylov) subspaces.
\end_layout

