\begin_layout Standard
The proximal operator for 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(\cdot|S)$
\end_inset

 is given as the projection on the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\prox_{\delta(\cdot|B(\epsilon,f))}(s)=\begin{cases}
f+\epsilon\frac{s-f}{\|s-f\|_{2}}, & \|s-f\|_{2}>\epsilon,\\
s, & \|s-f\|_{2}\leq\epsilon,
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

and, component-wise,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\prox_{\delta(\cdot|[0,1]^{n}))}(s)_{i}=\begin{cases}
0, & s_{i}\leq0,\\
s_{i}, & 0<s_{i}<1,\\
\beta, & s_{i}\geq1.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

The proximal operator for the 1-dimensional total variation can be computed
 with e.g.
 Condat's taut string algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Condat-2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

