\end_inset

 denotes the 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times m$
\end_inset

 matrix with orthonormal column vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1},\ldots,v_{m}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{m}$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Formula $(m+1)\times m$
\end_inset

 upper Hessenberg matrix
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
all zero entries below the subdiagonal
\end_layout

\end_inset

 with nonzero entries 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{ij}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a linear system 
\begin_inset Formula $Au=f$
\end_inset

, Krylov subspace methods extract an approximate solution 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{m}$
\end_inset

 from the affine subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}+\mathcal{K}_{m}(A,r_{0})$
\end_inset

 of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, by imposing the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $b-Au_{m}\bot\mathcal{L}_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{m}$
\end_inset

 is another subspace of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

general projection method
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}$
\end_inset

 represents an arbitrary initial guess to the solution, and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0}=b-Au_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the initial residual.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{m}=A\mathcal{K}_{m}$
\end_inset

, the method minimizes the 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

-norm of the residual 
\begin_inset Formula $b-Ax$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in x_{0}+\mathcal{K}_{m}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Proposition 5.3"
key "Saad-2003"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Such a method (e.g.
 GMRES) can work with general non-symmetric matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, provided they are non-singular.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can now state the following proposition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:krylov-least-squares"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Proposition 3"
key "Yun-2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\emph on
Under the assumption 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in u_{0}+\mathcal{K}_{m}(A,r_{0})$
\end_inset

, the least squares problem on line 3 of Algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "alg:ADMM-2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is reduced to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\min_{\alpha\in\mathbb{R}^{m}}\left\Vert \begin{bmatrix}H_{m}\\
\overline{G}_{2}\\
\vdots\\
\overline{G}_{J}
\end{bmatrix}\alpha-\begin{bmatrix}Q_{m+1}^{T}(v_{1}+d_{1})\\
Q_{m}^{T}(v_{2}+d_{2})\\
\vdots\\
Q_{m}^{T}(v_{J}+d_{J})
\end{bmatrix}\right\Vert _{2}^{2}\label{eq:krylov-least-squares}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{G}_{j}:=Q_{m}^{T}G_{j}Q_{+m}\in\mathbb{R}^{m\times m}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $j=2,\dots,J$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\emph on
Check dimensions
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\emph on
It has a unique solution if 
\begin_inset Formula $[H_{m}\cdots]$
\end_inset

 is of full rank
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

