\begin_layout Standard
The spatially variant Gaussian blur model in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Berisha-2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is used for the restoration experiments.
 The blur kernel at the pixel location 
\begin_inset Formula $s=(s_{1},s_{2})$
\end_inset

 in the image acquisition model 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
add ref
\end_layout

\end_inset

is obtained from the two-dimensional separable Gaussian function
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p(s,t) & =\frac{1}{\xi_{1}\xi_{2}}\exp\left(-\frac{1}{2}\frac{(t_{1}-s_{1})^{2}}{\sigma_{x}^{2}(s_{1})}+\frac{(t_{2}-s_{2})^{2}}{\sigma_{y}^{2}(s_{2})}\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

with normalizing constants 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\xi_{1}=\sqrt{2\pi}\sigma_{x}(s_{1}),\quad\xi_{2}=\sqrt{2\pi}\sigma_{y}(s_{2}).
\]

\end_inset

The blur kernel changes depending on the location 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, and hence the blur is spatially variant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
\begin_inset Formula $p(x,y)$
\end_inset

 is seperable, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(s,t)=p_{1}(s_{1},t_{1})\,p_{2}(s_{2},t_{2})
\]

\end_inset

holds with
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p_{1}(s_{1},t_{1}) & =\frac{1}{\xi_{1}}\exp\left\{ -\frac{1}{2}\frac{(t_{1}-s_{1})^{2}}{\sigma_{x}^{2}(s_{1})}\right\} \\
p_{2}(s_{2},t_{2}) & =\frac{1}{\xi_{2}}\exp\left\{ -\frac{1}{2}\frac{(t_{2}-s_{2})^{2}}{\sigma_{y}^{2}(s_{2})}\right\} 
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This means we can represent the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 as a Kroneker product 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}\otimes A_{2}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

 the 1-dimensional blur matrices 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "4.1.1"
key "Hansen-2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for a given boundary condition 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "2.2.5"
key "Berisha-2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Yun-2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, three types of spatially variant blur are considered.
 The first type has a smaller amount of blur at the center and a larger
 amount of blur at the corners of an image.
 The variances are given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma_{x}(s_{1}) & =\gamma|0.5-s_{1}/M|+0.5,\\
\sigma_{y}(s_{2}) & =\gamma|0.5-s_{2}/N|+0.5.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The second type is the opposite of the first case, with more severe blur
 at the center and milder blur at the corners.
 The variances are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma_{x}(s_{1}) & =-\gamma|0.5-s_{1}/M|+2.5,\\
\sigma_{y}(s_{2}) & =-\gamma|0.5-s_{2}/N|+2.5.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The third type has smaller amount of blur at the lower right corner and
 larger amount of blur at the upper left part of an image.
 The variances are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma_{x}(s_{1}) & =\gamma(0.5-s_{1}/M)/2+1.25,\\
\sigma_{y}(s_{2}) & =\gamma(0.5-s_{2}/N)/2+1.25.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is set fixed to 4, and 
\begin_inset Formula $21\times21$
\end_inset

 kernel size is used for discretization of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

